There are lots of different hobbyists. Some just like to drive, and let the others do the repairs. It's the same with guitar players too. Probably every hobby. Some guys are more fascinated by amps, circuitry, electrics and that's their thing. I've personally been more fascinated by guitar amps, distortion circuits etc. and started to learn diy electronics because I actually want to maintain some of the old stuff I own and just prolong their life. Just watched a project how some hifi enthusiast had totally restored some 70s hifi setup he dreamed as a kid and replaced all the electronics inside etc. to modern state. posts.com:
You can call me a pleb for ever liking this stuff. I don't even listen to NIN much at all anymore. Kinda a 2017-2018 phase. Anyhow, these songs are some of my favorites.


Copy of a - first NIN song I've ever heard. Feb 2017 was depressed, and this was reinvigorating

Sin - had to pick one from PHM, overrated LP but this track is fun

No, You Don't - Underrated song, similarly outwardly aggressive but also sadly overshadowed by the truly atrocious Starfuckers Inc

Head Down - awesome mid-life crisis song, though I connected to it being half way through my 20s and still a loser

Beside You In Time - nice enough cut from a mediocre album. Waaay better than the closer with that obvious melody and cringe lyric about seeing an animal in a cage

Gave Up - one of the best in Trent's entire discography

The Becoming - again one of the best

The Day The World Went Away (Still) - This version far surpasses the original. It's bitter sweat, sad yet comforting especially the second half

Over and Out - Easily the most relatable 4me

I'd try some other reverb, but this exact Altiverb IR sounds fucking perfect for this roomy techno, it pisses me off.

posts.com:
There's an interesting dichotomy in these songs that puts the difference in Paul and John's approach to music on display.

Paul's Christmas song is joyful and celebratory. John's is socially-conscious and frankly, a bit of a scold - "So this is Christmas, and what have you done?" Geez, I dunno John, what did I have to do besides wrap the presents and drink some eggnog?"

I mean I love them both, but Paul is much more the pure musician than John. John was compelled to deliver a moral lesson in his songs, whereas Paul was content to simply deliver a song.

I mean, if you feel that rock and roll music should be utilized to change the world, there's no real argument to that. I suppose the counterargument might be, no, actually it's only for having a good time.

Ultimately John never offered any solutions, only the scolding. "We must have peace!" But how, John? Someone evil is definitely going to start a war if the rest of us start lollygagging around peacefully, and it's not going to be pretty. Nice message but where's the REST of the message?

Paul>John - Paul will be universally mourned when he dies, he's truly a musician of and for the people. John? Some people were probably secretly tired of hearing him gripe at them all the time.

I'm looking for a download of a compilation bootleg called The Birth of Grateful Dead. (NOT to be confused with the official release entitled Birth of The Dead)

posts.com:
>firefox
1. browsers are convenient universal file viewers.

with chromium, i can drag a file from my explorer to my side monitor playing a youtube video, and it'll open up that file in a new tab, and switch to it immediately.

with firefox, that would replace the youtube page instead of opening a new tab, stopping the video i would've wanted to keep playing, and making me lose whatever temporary data was on that page. eg, a 4chan page with a wip comment

to do it correctly in firefox,
i'd have to leave fullscreen (more on this in a sec),
drag the file onto the title bar, not the page body,
then click on that new tab, because firefox doesn't immediately switch to it.

2. the general usability of youtube on firefox is just bad.

it's slower to leave fullscreen on firefox, because there are fade transitions. on chromium, it's an instantaneous switch.

to exit fullscreen, you can either click the bottom right button or the top dropdown button.
it's much harder to hit the bottom right button, because you can overshoot it
horizontally, and move your mouse into the other monitor space, and
vertically, pulling up the taskbar, now obscuring the fullscreen button

so the best option is the top middle button.
on chromium, that dropdown button comes out instantaneously.
on firefox, you have to leave your mouse up there for like a second before it slides down.

and then when it comes to just navigating youtube, it feels really sluggish.
i swore it had to have just been my imagination, but i even looked up and saw articles of the firefox dev complaining about google intentionally gimping firefox connections.
which is bullshit, sure, but that's not my fight to care about.
all it means is that it sucks to browse youtube with firefox.

if there are solutions to those problems, i'd like to hear them
because firefox has some cute customizations i miss

>chrome
i don't know of any difference between the two, because chromium is chromium.
so the only difference is superficial, desu
